annotation.TEXT: Several film sequels followed. In ‘92 it was turned into a TV series starring Adrian Paul as the title immortal, which ran for six years.
Les Ballets Trockadero de Monte Carlo is an all-male, all-drag ballet company based in New York City.
“Please don’t squeeze the Charmin” was the longtime slogan for Charmin toilet paper. The line was spoken by “Mr. Whipple,” played by Dick Wilson in more than 500 ads.
An imitation of Jim Nabors as Gomer Pyle, whom he played on The Andy Griffith Show and Gomer Pyle, U.S.M.C.
An imitation of scatterbrained Hank Kimball (played by Alvy Moore) from the TV sitcom Green Acres.
Forever Young stars Mel Gibson as a pilot who is cryogenically frozen in the ‘30s and defrosted in the ‘90s.
We hope you enjoyed this fully-annotated presentation of Alien from L.A.
The portly comedian John Candy became well-known on the Canadian comedy show SCTV and later in many films.
Steel Magnolias is a film about a group of friends hanging out at a local beauty parlor; it stars Sally Field, Dolly Parton, and Shirley MacLaine, among others.
Some amusement arcades still have machines challenging you to “Test Your Sex Appeal” (levels range from something like “Blah” to “Hot Stuff”).
Mad Max is a movie starring the then-unknown Mel Gibson as a disillusioned cop in a dystopian world.
A line from the song “Achy Breaky Heart” by country singer Billy Ray Cyrus, a favorite with line dancers during the ‘90s.
Did we miss any references? Let us know in the comments!
Bronson Pinchot is an actor best known for his turn as Balki Bartokomous on the TV sitcom Perfect Strangers.
A paraphrase of a line from the Beatles song “A Day in the Life.”
The unofficial motto of the U.S. Postal Service begins, “Neither snow nor rain nor heat …” It is a translation from the Greek historian Herodotus.
Poopdeck Pappy was Popeye’s father in the series of short cartoons by the same name.
Rich and Famous stars Candice Bergen and Jacqueline Bisset as two college friends whose relationship changes and endures over the years.
Edgar Winter is an albino blues/jazz/experimental musician whose best-known song is “Frankenstein,” which hit #1 in 1973.
Places in the Heart stars Sally Field as a widow trying to run a cotton farm.
The Schlepcar was a purple talking dune buggy on The Krofft Supershow, a live-action Saturday morning kids’ show. The Schlep Car could turn into Wonderbug, the superhero car.
Marlboro box means Marlboro cigarettes that come in a cardboard box as opposed to a soft pack.
In 1988 the Suzuki Samurai became notorious for rolling over in accidents. More than 200 people have died, but Suzuki avoided admitting any wrongdoing by settling out of court.
An Evening at the Improv was a TV series that showcased standup comedians. It aired from 1982-96.
An imitation of actor and avid golfer Bob Hope.
Golden Girls was a TV sitcom about a group of older women who lived together in Miami; it aired from 1985-92.
Men Don’t Leave stars Jessica Lange as the widowed mother of two sons.
Fred Rogers was the much-loved host of the children’s show Mister Rogers’ Neighborhood, which aired on PBS from 1968-2001.
A line from the traditional song “The Farmer in the Dell,” which originated in Germany.
The bearded, disheveled Jerry Garcia was the singer, songwriter, and lead guitarist for the Grateful Dead.
Marc Singer is an actor best known as the Beastmaster in the film of the same name and as Mike Donovan in the alien-invasion miniseries V.
“Kiss my grits” was the catch phrase of Flo, the “sassy” Texan waitress on the TV series Alice and its unsuccessful spinoff Flo.
The Métro de Paris is the urban transit system, largely underground, in Paris, France. It first opened in 1900 during the World’s Fair.
A high holiday is a Jewish holy day of special observance, such as Rosh Hashanah or Yom Kippur.
A paraphrase of a line from the 1982 film Blade Runner.
Singer J.P. “The Big Bopper” Richardson had a big hit in 1958 with “Chantilly Lace,” which begins with “Hello baby …”
Another reference to Casablanca; the original line is “We’ll always have Paris.” A batholith is a large mass of igneous rock produced by volcanic activity.
An imitation of renowned voiceover artist Rex Allen, who narrated Disney’s Charlie, the Lonesome Cougar, among many others.
Candy Slice was the punk rocker character, loosely based on Patti Smith, created by Gilda Radner on Saturday Night Live.
Fried Green Tomatoes is a film about a troubled wife who befriends an old woman in a nursing home.
Artist Andy Warhol was one of the founders of the Pop Art movement. He collected a group of eccentric hangers-on and wannabes in his New York studio.
Pepperidge Farms has been making Goldfish cheese-flavored snack crackers for more than 50 years.
Mark Hamill became a Hollywood icon playing Luke Skywalker in the original trilogy of Star Wars films. He went on to become a successful voiceover actor.
Miranda Richardson is a British actress who has appeared in such films as The Crying Game and Sleepy Hollow.
Let us know if we missed any references!
The Four Seasons is a film about three couples who get together regularly throughout the year; it stars Alan Alda and Carol Burnett, among others.
Where’s Waldo? is a series of picture books that ask the reader to find Waldo, a fellow clad in a striped shirt and hat, among an enormous crowd of people.
Highlander was a film about a race of immortals living among humans; it ends with an epic blue-lit swordfight before a wall of windows.
Though Tom seems to be imitating the horns from the soundtrack of Patton, he was probably thinking of Chariots of Fire, given the beach running.
In the game of rugby, a scrum involves closely packed players basically scrambling for the ball.
Saks Fifth Avenue is a chain of upscale department stores founded in 1924.
In the mockumentary This Is Spinal Tap, the hapless heavy metal band gets hopelessly lost in a maze of corridors on their way to the stage for a concert in Cleveland.
The theme from the British “spy-fi” series The Avengers was based on “The Shake” dance craze of the ‘60s.
An imitation of Count Floyd (Joe Flaherty), who hosted Monster Chiller Horror Theater on the Canadian late night sketch comedy show SCTV.
Campho-Phenique is an OTC product used to treat cold sores; it is made by the Bayer Corp.
Actor Michael Knight played Tad Martin on the soap opera All My Children from 1982 until the series finale in 2011; he won two daytime Emmys for the role.
A reference to the Bette Midler song “Wing Beneath My Wings,” which was the theme to her movie Beaches.
A paraphrased line from the song “Computer Blue” by Minneapolis musician Prince, off his classic album Purple Rain.
That was actually model Paulina Porizkova, in the 1987 swimsuit issue.
Coleman manufactures the familiar lanterns used by campers everywhere, in addition to coolers and other outdoorsy equipment.
Pert Plus is a brand of shampoo plus conditioner manufactured by Procter & Gamble.
Don’t Tell Her It’s Me is a film about a lonely cartoonist (Steve Guttenberg) whose sister sets him up with a beautiful woman.
Israeli businessmen Menahem Golan and Yoram Globus owned Cannon Films in the ‘80s, producing some of the decade’s cheesiest films.
A paraphrase of Martin Sheen’s famous line from the film Apocalypse Now.
Boy George is a flamboyant new wave singer who scored major hits with his band Culture Club in the early ‘80s with “Do You Really Want to Hurt Me” and “Karma Chameleon.”
A variation on the classic buffet injunction: “Take all you want, but eat all you take.”
Vanity made it big in 1982 with the group Vanity 6, with the hit song “Nasty Girl.” The group was a spinoff from the Prince empire.
The Blue Mosque is a mosque in Istanbul; it got its nickname for the color of its tile work. It is on the first hill (of seven) in the city.
A line from the song “Maniac,” from the soundtrack of the 1983 movie Flashdance.
The “T-zone,” a term coined by the beauty industry to describe a purported problem area, is the area formed by the forehead, nose, and mouth.
Herbert Ross directed such films as Steel Magnolias and Boys on the Side.
A rendition of the theme from the groovy ‘60s TV show The Mod Squad. The show’s opening involved a lot of running.
Peter Greenaway is a film director whose oeuvre includes The Belly of an Architect and The Cook, the Thief, His Wife & Her Lover.
Orkin is a national pest-removal company that used to run ads with the “Orkin Army,” a battalion of exterminators. The Orkin Army has since been replaced by the Orkin Man.
Amadeus is a crowd-pleasing film about composer Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, based on the play of the same name.
An imitation of Inspector Jacques Clouseau, as played by Peter Sellers in the Pink Panther movies.
Captain Ron is a notoriously bad film starring Kurt Russell as a one-eyed, maniacal sailor in the Caribbean.
Mad Max Beyond Thunderdome is the third film starring Mel Gibson as the anti-hero, forced to go up against Tina Turner’s chainmail dress in the arena known as Thunderdome.
Manchester United is an extremely famous pro soccer team based in Manchester, England.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Frankenberry is a fruit-flavored children’s cereal with a Frankenstein’s monster mascot, in the same line as Count Chocula.
On The Andy Griffith Show, Mount Pilot was a nearby large town the characters would visit when they wanted some excitement. Sarah was the unseen phone operator on the show.
Did we miss one? Let us know in the comments!
Renaissance Festivals began in SoCal in the ‘60s. They have vendors selling swords, leather mugs, jewelry, etc.; performers; a “royal court”; and rides and games.
“Toys in the attic” is a traditional insult, implying that the person referred to is a little short of the essential gray matter.
A paraphrase of the classic line from the Jimmy Cagney film White Heat: “Made it, Ma! Top of the world!”
Donald Pleasence was a bald actor known for playing Ernst Blofeld in You Only Live Twice and Dr. Sam Loomis in the Halloween horror films.
A shillelagh (aka a cudgel) is a roughly 2-foot-long club/walking stick traditionally carried in Ireland.
Dying Young stars Julia Roberts as a young woman who falls in love with a man suffering from a terminal illness.
Cathy Smith was a backup singer/groupie/drug dealer who served 15 months in prison for injecting comedian John Belushi with the mixture of cocaine and heroin that killed him.
The opening line from every episode of the ‘50s sitcom The Bob Cummings Show (aka Love That Bob), which was about a photographer.
Paul Westerberg was the front man for the ‘80s band The Replacements.
Chili’s Grill & Bar is a chain of “family restaurants” serving mid-priced meals such as ribs, fajitas, steaks, buffalo wings, etc.
Jujubes are a type of gelatin candy that were a staple of movie theater snack bars throughout the ‘50s and ‘60s.
Atlanta, GA, is home to the CNN Center, headquarters of news network CNN. CNN was founded by Ted Turner, who also owned the Atlanta Braves baseball team until 2007.
The first line from the song “Heart of Glass” by the band Blondie.
Ford Motor Co. is one of the world's oldest automakers, founded in 1903 by Henry Ford.
Looking for Mr. Goodbar is a movie (based on a novel by the same name) starring Diane Keaton as a teacher who begins cruising bars at night to pick up guys.
On Baywatch, Hobie Buchannon was played by Brandon Call and more famously by Jeremy Jackson. “Lieutenant” is probably Lt. Stephanie Holden (Alexandra Paul).
This was the slogan for the Midas chain of muffler and brake repair shops from the mid-‘70s to the early ‘90s.
Conrad Janis is a balding musician and actor who has appeared in many films and TV shows, including Mork & Mindy and Airport 1975.
Clint Howard, brother of actor/director Ron Howard, has appeared in such films as Apollo 13 and Austin Powers: International Man of Mystery.
Stella stars Bette Midler as a vulgar woman who sacrifices everything for the sake of her daughter. It is a remake of Stella Dallas.
Singer Janet Jackson is the sister of King of Pop Michael Jackson. At the ’93 Video Music Awards, she performed in jeans and a leather bra; her abs were the star of the show.
The Theatre de la Jeune Lune was an oddball theater company based in Minneapolis.
Filene’s Basement was a chain of discount department stores based in Boston. It went under in 2011.
In the Mr. Creosote segment in the film Monty Python’s Meaning of Life, an enormously fat man keeps vomiting into a bucket during his meal in a classy restaurant.
Savannah Smiles is about a young girl who runs away and hides in the trunk of a car belonging to a couple of crooks, who are pursued for “kidnapping” her.
2 Calorie Quest was a flavored carbonated water manufactured by Seagram’s in the ‘90s.
Structure was a chain of mall men’s clothing stores. They rebranded under the Express name in the early aughts and Sears bought the rights to the old brand.
Get the inside scoop behind every reference.
Nina Petrovna Khrushcheva was the second wife of Soviet premier Nikita Khrushchev, who led the Soviet Union from 1953-64. His first wife died of typhus c. 1920.
A line from the song “Funkytown” by Lipps Inc.
The Walker Art Center is a center for the performing & visual arts in Minneapolis. Six Weeks is a film about a woman (Mary Tyler Moore) whose daughter is dying from leukemia.
Twins Matthew and Gunnar Nelson make up the core of the ‘90s rock band The Nelsons, which had hits such as “Love and Affection.”
“Wicked” Nick Bockwinkle was a professional wrestler for 25 years. When he was AWA champion, he was often photographed in his championship belt, which had a buckle the size of a man’s head.
World champion gymnast Kurt Thomas made the wonderfully bad movie Gymkata, in which he defeats the bad guys with the help of randomly placed gymnastics equipment.
Ice Castles is a tear-jerker about a blind ice skater, played by Lynn-Holly Johnson.
There were mall food court restaurants called the Great Hot Dog Experience owned by a Minneapolis company, but A&W bought them in 1997 and the name is no more.
Tennis player John McEnroe won seven Grand Slam single and nine double titles, but is best remembered for his hot temper and frequent outbursts on the court.
Cousins is about two married people (played by Ted Danson and Isabella Rossellini) who fall in love.
A line from the song “One Night in Bangkok,” from the musical Chess, which was released as a single by Murray Head.
Days of Our Lives is a daytime soap opera that follows the lives and loves of the residents of the fictional town of Salem.
Renegade was a TV show starring Lorenzo Lamas as an unjustly accused man on the run from the law.
A green card is given to a non-citizen who has the right to permanently live and work in the U.S. Cards given to immigrants after WWII were green.
Adam Ant is a new wave musician whose biggest hit was 1982’s “Goody Two Shoes.”
In the TV series The Addams Family, the tiny Cousin Itt was completely covered in long hair and spoke in an unintelligible squeak.
Pagliacci is an opera about a troupe of traveling actors and a husband’s jealousy that ends in violence.
Madame Marie Curie was a Nobel Prize-winning physicist who, with her husband Pierre, discovered two new elements and first identified radioactivity in such elements as uranium.
A reference to the famous balcony scene in William Shakespeare’s romantic tragedy Romeo and Juliet.
The U.S. Navy adopted a gyroscope autopilot invented by Elmer Sperry, which was known colloquially as “Metal Mike,” in its planes in the first half of the 20th century.
Down the Shore was a TV series about a group of guys sharing a beach house. Kathy Ireland guest-starred on one episode.
Stuarts was a chain of discount clothing stores for women. It went under in the mid-‘90s.
A paraphrase of a line from the song “Another Brick in the Wall,” from the famed Pink Floyd rock opera The Wall.
In the TV sitcom Cheers, Norm Peterson (George Wendt) was traditionally greeted on his entrance to the bar with a cry of “Norm!”
The OTC medicines Sudafed and Nyquil contain chemicals such as pseudoephedrine and dextromethorphan, which some people (mainly teenagers) use to get high.
Actor Kiefer Sutherland has appeared in such films as The Lost Boys and starred in the TV series 24.
Liviu Ciulei was the artistic director of the Guthrie Theater, a performing arts center in Minneapolis, from 1980-85.
Always stars Richard Dreyfuss as a ghost firefighter trying to protect his lover, played by Holly Hunter.
Kirby Puckett played center field for the Minnesota Twins from 1984 until glaucoma ended his career in 1995.
William Burroughs’ most famous novel is Naked Lunch, one of the seminal books of the Beat generation. He was also addicted to heroin, a theme in many of his works.
A line from the Tom Waits song “Underground.”
Leroy and Loretta Lockhorn are a married couple who hurl hurtful barbs at each other every day in the syndicated comic strip “The Lockhorns.”
A reference to Show 417, Crash of the Moons.
Oceania is one of the three superpower blocs in George Orwell’s novel Nineteen Eighty-Four. The other two are Eurasia and Eastasia.
Sherman Hemsley was best known for playing the irascible George Jefferson on All in the Family and then on its spinoff The Jeffersons.
Sam Giancana was the top Mafia boss in Chicago from 1957-66. He was gunned down in 1975 soon after his return to the U.S. after 7 years abroad.
The title of the movie is actually Shy People, a film about the clash between country folk and city folk.
Gracie Allen and her husband George Burns made up the comedy team Burns & Allen. They are both interred in the marble-clad Freedom Mausoleum in Forest Lawn in Glendale.
The Young Indiana Jones Chronicles was a TV series that featured Indiana Jones at three ages: an old man, who narrated the episodes; a boy of 10; and a young man in his late teens.
Campbell Scott plays the young man suffering from leukemia in Dying Young.
Robert Fulghum is the author of Everything I Need to Know I Learned in Kindergarten, a collection of short ruminations on life first published in 1988.
Metalstorm: The Destruction of Jared-Syn was a fantasy film produced during the brief revival of 3-D in the early ‘80s.
Mermaids stars Cher as a woman in the ‘60s trying to deal with her conflicted religious daughter (Winona Ryder).
Devo was a geek-rock/new-wave band in the ‘80s. Their first album was titled Q: Are We Not Men? A: We Are Devo! Drummer Alan Myers was known for wearing clear goggles.
Ian Anderson is the lead singer and flautist for the rock band Jethro Tull.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website
Joe Mantegna is an actor known for such films as The Godfather Part III, but also for playing Fat Tony on the animated TV series The Simpsons.
“Ganj” is slang for marijuana.
In the Warner Bros. cartoons, Wile E. Coyote’s efforts to catch and eat the Road Runner often end in his falling off a cliff to land in a puff of dust.
A famous line from the film The Last of the Mohicans, spoken by Daniel Day-Lewis.
Ray Stevens is a musician/comedian known for his novelty songs such as “The Streak” and “Ahab the Arab.”
Spencer Tracy and Katharine Hepburn co-starred in nine classic films. They were known for their sparkling repartee; they were also a couple in real life for 26 years.
A paraphrase of the song “Night Life” by Willie Nelson, also recorded by Ray Price and B.B. King.
For the Boys stars Bette Midler and James Caan as entertainers during World War II.
A paraphrase of the song “Rough Boys” by Pete Townshend.
Hellraiser was a horror film about a man who discovers a gateway to hell. The sequel was actually called Hellbound: Hellraiser II.
Charles Dickens created such an evocative portrayal of 19th-century British life in works like Oliver Twist that the adjective “Dickensian” was coined to describe it.
Franklin Mint makes collectible coins, plates, dolls, etc. They often promote some recent pop culture icon or event, captured in a “limited edition” coin or plate.
The Big Mac burger from McDonald’s was advertised for years as consisting of “two all-beef patties, special sauce, lettuce, cheese, pickles, onions on a sesame seed bun.”
Death Wish V: The Face of Death stars Charles Bronson in his fifth and final appearance as vigilante Paul Kersey.
Tommy is a rock opera by The Who, about a boy who is deaf, dumb, and blind but who nonetheless plays a mean game of pinball. The album cover shows a metallic silver grid.
Mystic Pizza stars Julia Roberts, Annabeth Gish, and Lili Taylor as three young women working in a pizza parlor in Connecticut.
Doug Henning was a hippie magician with long hair and a drooping mustache who became famous in the ‘70s with a successful Broadway show.
Pearle Vision is a nationwide chain of eyeglass stores founded in 1961 by Dr. Stanley Pearle.
The Life and Times of Grizzly Adams was a film and TV series starring Dan Haggerty as a man who lives in the mountains with his pet bear.
Vertigo is an Alfred Hitchcock film starring Jimmy Stewart as a detective with a phobia about heights and an obsession with a beautiful, mysterious woman.
Suzy Favor Hamilton is a professional runner who has competed in the Olympics and was ranked top in the U.S. for several years.
Archie Rice (played by Laurence Olivier) is the main character in The Entertainer, a film about a third-rate performer in a failing show at a dying seaside resort.
Late for Dinner is a film about two young men who are cryogenically frozen in the ‘60s and thawed in the ‘90s.
Baywatch was a TV series about lifeguards on a resort beach that starred David Hasselhoff.
Sonny Spoon was a short-lived TV series starring Mario Van Peebles as a P.I./con man who specialized in bilking criminals.
A famous line from the film Highlander.
Shock jock Howard Stern has for more than 30 years been willing to do anything to shock and amuse his listeners (and annoy his critics) on The Howard Stern Show.
Only Elle MacPherson has appeared on the cover of the swimsuit issue more times than Ireland (5 vs. 3).
A reference to the song “The Lollipop Guild” from the film musical The Wizard of Oz.
From 1981-1990, the minimum wage was stuck at $3.35/hour, a record not broken until the wage freeze that lasted from 1997-2007.
Edie Sedgwick appeared in a number of Andy Warhol’s films. She lived at the Chelsea Hotel in New York, where she once famously set her room on fire.
Guitarist Ted “The Nuge” Nugent is equally well known for his hard rock albums such as Cat Scratch Fever as for his right-wing political views and pro-gun advocacy.
Count Chocula is a chocolate-flavored children’s cereal. The Count himself, bearing a strong resemblance to Bela Lugosi’s Dracula, appeared in animated ads for the cereal.
The Lemon Sisters is a film about three friends trying to make it as an entertainment trio in Atlantic City.
Sizzle Beach, U.S.A. is a T&A movie about three women trying to make it in L.A. Notable only for a young Kevin Costner in a small role.
Tom is imitating a muezzin, who calls the Islamic faithful to pray five times a day. He finishes by yodeling, a form of singing that originated in the Austrian Alps.
The Wild Mouse is a type of roller coaster that is easily assembled and disassembled, and therefore is popular among traveling carnivals and fairs.
Rube Goldberg was a cartoonist who created drawings of wildly overelaborate machinery that performed some basic task like licking stamps.
The video for the Aerosmith song “Love in an Elevator” begins with a sultry woman saying, “Good morning, Mr. Tyler. Going … down?”
The Lady Derringer is a line of small handguns designed to appeal to women. Thuringer is a type of smoked sausage.
The Goodbye Girl is a romantic comedy starring Marsha Mason and Richard Dreyfuss.
The new wave movement of rock followed the DIY punks of the ‘70s but was more polished and professional. Bands included Talking Heads and Blondie.
Exene Cervenka is a punk musician who was one of the founding members of the seminal SoCal punk band X.
“Yakety Sax” by Boots Randolph was often used during sped-up chases on the British skit comedy show The Benny Hill Show, which ran for 20 years.
Patchouli is a fragrant herb commonly used to make perfume. It was extremely popular during the ‘60s and has become associated with the counterculture of that decade.
Probably a reference to the Cole Porter song “I Love Paris”: ”I love Paris in the springtime …”
Really a darn good imitation of the sound made by lightsabers in the immensely popular Star Wars movies.
Godspell is a musical based on the Gospel according to St. Matthew.
A take on the longtime jingle for Wrigley’s Doublemint gum, which has been running ads featuring identical twins for decades.
Napoléon is a 1927 silent film about the French emperor and general. It was written and directed by French filmmaker Abel Gance.
Down the Shore lasted two seasons on Fox. Anna Gunn (Skyler on Breaking Bad) got her first acting break on the show.
Crow is correct. The Douglas DC-3 was the most popular plane during the ‘30s; more than 16,000 of them were made.
A line from the song “The Surrey with the Fringe on Top,” from the musical Oklahoma!
Blond actress Janet Leigh is most famous for being stabbed to death in the shower scene in Psycho.
The Children’s Hour is a play by Lillian Hellman set at a girls’ school, where a mischief-making student accuses her headmistresses of being lesbians.
Short Round was Indiana Jones’s young sidekick in the film Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom.
The band Survivor is best known for its hit “Eye of the Tiger,” the theme song for the film Rocky III.
Hash or hashish is a drug derived from the oil of the cannabis sativa plant, as opposed to marijuana, which is the dried flowers of the same plant.
This is the opening line to the song “Do-Re-Mi” from The Sound of Music.
Our Town is a play by Thornton Wilder about life in the small town of Grover’s Corners.
A famous line from the pilot for the TV sitcom The Mary Tyler Moore Show.
An imitation of Oliver Hardy, along with Stan Laurel half of the comedy team Laurel & Hardy, which made a string of movies during the ‘20s and ’30s.
Madame Sousatzka stars Shirley MacLaine as an eccentric piano teacher in London.
Tina Turner had a popular R&B act with her husband Ike in the late ‘60s and early ‘70s before divorcing him and launching a stunningly successful solo career.
Mother Teresa was a nun who worked with the poor in Calcutta and founded a religious order there. The Church started the sainthood process six years after her death.
Arne Saknussemm, BTW, was an explorer in the Jules Verne novel A Journey to the Center of the Earth.
A line from MST3K Episode 303, Pod People.
Home Alone was a film about a young boy left behind to battle two burglars when his family goes on a trip. It spawned three sequels and two made-for-TV movies..
The song “Oh Yeah” by Swiss electronic band Yello was made famous by the ‘80s movies Ferris Bueller’s Day Off and The Secret of My Success.
Guitarist Eddie Van Halen, founder of the band that bears his name, is widely considered one of the most talented guitarists in rock & roll.
Starwolf was the alternate name of Ken in the Fugitive Alien series, featured in Episodes K03, K12, 310, and 318.
Golan and Globus were also responsible for Delta Force, The Barbarians, and Breakin’ 2: Electric Boogaloo, among many others.
A line from the song “Abraham, Martin, and John,” written by Dick Holler and recorded by Dion and Marvin Gaye, among others.
Not Without My Daughter stars Sally Field as an American woman trying to leave Iran with her daughter against the wishes of her Iranian husband.
Irreconcilable Differences stars Drew Barrymore as a young girl who sues to divorce her bickering parents.
Switcheroo is an old magic trick in which the magician passes two objects rapidly between his hands. It involves no sleight of hand—merely lots of dexterity and practice.
A paraphrase of Humphrey Bogart’s famous line from Casablanca: “The problems of three little people don’t amount to a hill of beans in this crazy world.”
David Brinkley was a TV journalist who hosted the news program This Week with David Brinkley. He was known for his clipped delivery and sardonic wit.
Kid Creole & the Coconuts is a retro band that plays a combination of funk, big band, and swing. Bandleader Kid Creole is actually musician August Darnell.
This appears to be an imitation of the many ads for attorneys on late-night TV.
Shaft in Africa was a blaxploitation film starring Richard Roundtree as John Shaft, a Los Angeles P.I. who tries to break up a modern-day slave trade in West Africa.
Jim McMahon played quarterback for six pro teams including the Bears. He was known as “the punky QB.”
In an episode of The Andy Griffith Show, Andy and his love interest, Helen Crump, are trapped in a cave, and Barney tries to come to their rescue.
Woody Harrelson rose to fame as the sweet, naïve bartender Woody Boyd on the TV sitcom Cheers. He has also acted in many films.
An imitation of the sound effect used on the TV series The Six Million Dollar Manwhen title character Steve Austin ran in slow motion, to indicate he was actually running very, very fast.
True. The film was mostly shot in South Africa, with some scenes filmed in Namibia.
LensCrafters is a chain of eyeglass stores that promises its clients their glasses will be ready in “about an hour.”
An imitation of the guards’ chant outside the Wicked Witch of the West’s castle in The Wizard of Oz.
The wait is over! Here comes the fully-annotated Alien from L.A.!
Joel Grey is a singer and actor best known for playing the Master of Ceremonies in the film and stage versions of Cabaret.
Paul Shaffer was the bandleader/sidekick on the TV talk shows Late Night with David Letterman and Late Show with David Letterman.
“Papa Don’t Preach” is a 1986 Madonna song that engendered some controversy at the time, on the grounds that it endorsed teen pregnancy.
Kathy Ireland has appeared in Sports Illustrated magazine’s annual swimsuit issue 13 times, more than any other model, and appeared on the cover 3 times.
Danny DeVito is a diminutive actor/director who came to fame playing irascible dispatcher Louie De Palma on the TV series Taxi. He has appeared in and directed many films.
Patti LaBelle is a singer best known for her iconic disco song “Lady Marmalade.”
“Guest workers” is a euphemism for undocumented immigrants who come to a country to find jobs; it is derived from the German word “Gastarbeiter.”
Wall Drug is a pharmacy/tourist trap in Wall, SD. For years it blanketed the nation’s highways with signs advising motorists how far they were from Wall Drug.
In the first book of The Lord of the Rings, the wizard Gandalf confronts a creature called a Balrog in the mines of Moria. He falls into an abyss with the monster and is presumed dead.
Yentl stars Barbra Streisand as a Jewish girl who disguises herself as a man to study the Torah.
A line from the opening scene of The Tempest by William Shakespeare.
An imitation of Jack Perkins, former host of A&E’s Biography. Mike Nelson parodied him in The Mystery Science Theater Hour.
Rush is a prog.-rock trio known for its impressive technical artistry. It formed in 1968 and remained popular throughout the ‘90s.
Cabaret is a musical set in Berlin during the Nazis’ rise to power.
Beaches stars Bette Midler and Barbara Hershey as two friends who share a conflicted friendship from childhood into adulthood.
Minnie Pearl was the stage name of actress Sarah Colley, who toured with the Grand Ole Opry from 1940-91. Her trademark entrance line was “How-dee!”
